[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(27) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "For the Son of man shall come.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The fact stands in a logical relation to the preceding verse. The fact that the Son of Man is about to come to execute judgment, clothes its abstract statement with an awful certainty. No bribe can be offered to the Eternal Judge to change the sentence of forfeiture if that forfeiture has been rightfully incurred. From first to last in our Lord’s teaching (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "e.g.,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for its earlier stages, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 7:23-24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 5:26-27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") this claim to be the future Judge of all men is never absent. It is asserted in every great discourse, implied in almost every parable.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "With his angels.—We are justified by Matthew 25:31 in referring the possessive pronoun to Christ rather than the Father. “All things that the Father hath are Mine” (John 16:15), and among these the angels that do His pleasure.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "With his angels.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—We are justified by ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 25:31",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " in referring the possessive pronoun to Christ rather than the Father. “All things that the Father hath are Mine” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 16:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), and among these the angels that do His pleasure.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "His works.—The better MSS. give a word in the singular, his doing or conduct. The sentence is made to depend on the collective character of what has been done rather than on the multitude of individual acts.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "His works.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The better MSS. give a word in the singular, his ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "doing",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " or ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "conduct.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " The sentence is made to depend on the collective character of what has been done rather than on the multitude of individual acts.",
            "children": []
          }
